If you are going to Epcot soon be sure to head over to the area near Journey into Imagination where the Captain EO attraction was located. They have replaced this attraction with a incredible preview of the movie which starts at the Worlds Fair in the 60's and gives you the backstory of the boy who will grow up into the character played by George Clooney. I must say my wife and I are both blown away by what we saw and some of the trailers give you bits and pieces but the preview in the park put everything together and added some additional content. We can't wait to see the movie and know it's going to be awesome.

text: It was okay. If your expectations aren't too high (unlike mine were) then I think you'll like it. There were some parts of the move that really were cool, but towards the end it just disappointed me more and more. The plot was a little shaky, and the events that occurred while they were actually in Tomorrowland weren't as cool as the trailers portrayed them to be. To be honest, the best parts of the movie were the parts where they weren't even in Tomorrowland. I was just super excited for this movie since I'm a huge fan of futuristic concepts like this, but overall it just really disappointed me and went below my expectations. The acting was pretty good though. Awkward at times, but still good. I just wish they expanded on the plot a lot more; they spent way too long showing the process of getting to Tomorrowland than what it was like to actually be there...

text: Tomorrowland what went wrong? Its been out for a while and now just about to come out on Blu ray and having seen the film twice now I can see where the film went wrong.  1. The Protagonist is the wrong person. The first 15 mins of Tomorrowland are the best part. It introduces a likable character Frank Walker who has an interesting story and character arc. If the film centered on Frank Walker and perhaps his daughter it would have been a more focused and nuanced story.  2. Casey Newton. Her character comes off as a very unlikable and abrasive know it all. Also they spend a lot of time introducing her brother and father who suddenly disappear half way through the film. Her character is more reactionary than having anything to do with the story or themes.  3. The Robots. The robots are the villains in Tomorrowland and don't come off as any kind of threat, they are overly cartoonish and almost impossible to take seriously. The solution make the bad guys Tomorrowland inductees turned bad with futuristic gadgets at their disposal.  4. The Environmental Message. Tomorrowland has a very heavy hand message about ecology and how we are destroying the planet. It comes off like a bad after school special. Perhaps the theme should be focused on inspiring humanity to be better rather than berating us about current sociological and political problems.  5. A waste of Hugh Laurie. By far the best part of this film is Hugh Laurie as David Nix but unfortunately he is hardly in the film. I was waiting for his character to be revealed as somewhat threatening and competent bad guy but that never happened. To make a bad guy interesting you have to make him relatable but again that never happened.  6. The Pins. This is an interesting plot device but hardly used in the story its more of a throw away plot device. If it was tied into the climax of the film it would have made more sense. Also the pins are very dangerous what if you touch one while crossing the street you will almost certainly be killed. At least address this in the film and upgrade them.  7. Ideas. This film has interesting ideas but doesnt know what to do with them. The concept of Tommorowland as utopia for the best and brightest is interesting but never followed through. The pins are interesting and unique  but are only used as a superficial plot device. The idea of kid who had big dreams but had them crushed and grew up to be old and bitter is interesting but never followed up upon.  Tomorrowland is all about ambition and inspiration but wasn't ambitious enough to try something new and push the envelope. It talked down to the audience not trusting the kids watching enough to think for themselves. The best stories challenge the audience to think and ponder after the credits have rolled but if they have already been told what to think and what conclusions to make then what is the point?

Seriously Disney, f**k you for spreading this kind of illusion to our new generation. We don't need hope, we need action. Maybe the best way to how bad things actually are is to let us suffer. And if you think world's bad, think 20 times worse, because we don't even get to see most of the sh*t that's happening in it. text: I *really* wanted to like this film, but I just couldn't. When the first teaser trailer released, I was floored. It seemed like such an original and cool concept! You can imagine my complete disappointment when I found that not only did they not get to Tomorrowland until the third act, but that Tomorrowland was practically a wasteland, and that what Casey saw was only an advertisement. Like a lot of reviewers said about this movie: "Tomorrowland is a film that I'm still waiting to see". This concept still has *so* much potential, and I *really* hope that Disney tries to reboot this at some point, though that will likely never happen.

text: Okay, so I saw this movie when it came out in theaters and was disappointed for its dystopian overtones -- but I watched it a couple days ago on DVD and actually really liked it. Maybe since I knew what to expect I could appreciate both the utopian and dystopian aspects -- and saw the movie had an overall positive theme. I still would have preferred a more whimsical 1960s-type movie with optimistic futuristic themes (maybe we could get a prequel or more optimistic sequel?) but I now feel it has a lot more potential than I initially thought it did.  Anyone else have that impression?

text: This movie is far from perfection (plot holes and whatever), but now I want to explore the cornerstone idea. Theorizing a world where only the smartest can access is pretty fascist. The idea is fascinating, but involves the concept of standard, that excludes by definition people that can't reach it. I'm ok with that, but only if the smartest payback the community with their work, and this isn't the case (in fact they are isolated in their city, located in a parallel dimension). This vision of the world represent an old Walt Disney obsession (and Walt was a well known conservative). Sorry for my english, I'm not a mother tongue! :)

text: The movie had a fantastic opening at the 1964 World's Fair and then it went downhill from there. Brad Bird made a somewhat entertaining but not at all exceptional film about a possible future for us all. This movie was bogged down by a depressing plot and an even more depressing Tomorrowland visit. I was hoping for a Jetson's style movie with amazing architecture and technology, but instead I got robots, climate change lectures, NASA closures and George Clooney being annoyed by his surroundings for two hours. Disney should have taken the 200+ million they spent on this and made TRON III instead.
